1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 {The mainline and 
the most challenging move. White develops and wants to ruin our structure by 
capturing on f6.} e6 {Opening the way for the f8 bishop and defends f6 not 
allowing our structure to deform.} 7. Qd2 {Queenside castling is on the way.} 
Be7 8. O-O-O O-O {The begins with both sides castling on opposite sides.} 9. f3 
{The most played move after 9. f4} Nxd4 {Forcing the White queen to the center 
and preparing a6-b5.} 10. Qxd4 a6 11. h4 {White starts with their own plans.} b5 
{We continue with our attack.} 12. Kb1 {A classical move for White in the 
Sicilian defense. White protects a2 for future Qa5-b4 ideas and removes his king 
from the open c-file.} Bb7 {Developing and clearing c8 for our rook.} 13. Qd2 
{White returns his Queen before developing his light-squared bishop.} Rc8 14. 
Bd3 Nd7 $13 {[%cal Bd7c5,Bd7e5,Gc8c3] Taking advantage of the fact that the 
d3-bishop has cut off the pressure on the d6. We also stop h5 for now and 
prepare to activate our knight to e5/c5-square. See Perez Candelario, M vs 
Malakhov, V.} *

