1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 {The mainline and 
the most challenging move. White develops and wants to ruin our structure by 
capturing on f6.} e6 {Opening the way for the f8 bishop and defends f6 not 
allowing our structure to deform.} 7. Qd2 {Queenside castling is on the way.} 
Be7 8. O-O-O O-O {The begins with both sides castling on opposite sides.} 9. f4 
{White gains space and supports e5. This is the most challenging move and some 
memorization will be needed here.} Nxd4 {Avoiding White's idea with Nxc6 and 
f4.} 10. Qxd4 Qa5 $1 {Activating the Queen, supporting d5/e5, and freeing the 
d8-square for the rook. Now White has many options.} 11. h4 {White supports his 
g5 and prepares e5.} d5 {We are ready to act in the center.} 12. Kb1 {White 
decides to leave the tension in the center and plays a useful move to safeguard 
a2.} Bc5 {Black plays in a similar way as in 12. e5.} 13. Qd3 Ng4 {Again, Black 
goes for the f2-square.} 14. Qg3 {White prepares kingside operations.} h5 15. 
exd5 {White opens the center now since a2 is well-defended.} Bb4 {f2 tricks will 
not work, so we should ruin White's structure.} 16. Rh3 {White supports the c3 
knight.} Bxc3 {We capture anyway benefiting from the g5-bishop's awkward 
positioning.} 17. Qxc3 Qxc3 18. Rxc3 f6 {Forcing White to give us our pawn 
back.} 19. dxe6 {White sets up a last trick.} Bxe6 $1 {Don't be greedy with 
19... fxg5 since 20. Bc4, supporting e6, will put us under White's mercy.} 20. 
f5 {White has no other way to save his g5-bishop.} Bxf5 {[%cal Ba8c8,Bg4e5] 
Reaching an equal endgame. White has the bishop pair, but we have active pieces 
and a nice outpost for our knight on the e5. After White retreats the g5-bishop, 
you can consider Rac8, exchanging rooks and keeping eye on the c2.} *

